### Error Handling Overview

Dart distinguishes between errors (programming mistakes) and exceptions (runtime problems).

| Type | Description | Examples |
|------|-------------|----------|
| `Error` | Programming bug | `RangeError`, `TypeError` |
| `Exception` | Runtime problem | `FormatException`, `IOException` |

### The Exception Class

```dart
void main() {
  // Built-in exceptions
  try {
    int.parse('not_a_number');
  } on FormatException catch (e) {
    print('Bad format: $e');
  }

  // Custom exception
  try {
    throw AgeException('Age must be 18+');
  } on AgeException catch (e) {
    print('Age error: ${e.message}');
  }
}

class AgeException implements Exception {
  final String message;
  AgeException(this.message);

  @override
  String toString() => 'AgeException: $message';
}
```

### Throwing Exceptions

```dart
void validateAge(int age) {
  if (age < 0) {
    throw ArgumentError('Age cannot be negative');
  }
  if (age < 18) {
    throw Exception('Must be 18 or older');
  }
}

void main() {
  try {
    validateAge(-5);
  } catch (e) {
    print('Validation failed: $e');
  }
}
```

### Custom Exceptions

```dart
class NetworkException implements Exception {
  final String message;
  final int statusCode;

  NetworkException(this.message, this.statusCode);

  @override
  String toString() => 'NetworkException($statusCode): $message';
}

void makeRequest(String url) {
  throw NetworkException('Not found', 404);
}

void main() {
  try {
    makeRequest('/api/data');
  } on NetworkException catch (e) {
    print('Network error ${e.statusCode}: ${e.message}');
  }
}
```

### Error vs Exception Distinction

```dart
void main() {
  // Error - should not be caught, fix the code
  // throw RangeError('Index out of bounds');

  // Exception - can be caught and handled
  try {
    throw Exception('Something went wrong');
  } catch (e) {
    print('Handled: $e');
  }
}
```

> **Key Point:** Implement the `Exception` interface for custom exceptions. Use `Error` subclasses for programming mistakes (bugs to fix), and `Exception` for runtime conditions to handle.

codeExample:
class ValidationException implements Exception {
  final String field;
  final String message;

  ValidationException(this.field, this.message);

  @override
  String toString() => 'Validation failed for $field: $message';
}

void validateUser(String name, int age) {
  if (name.isEmpty) {
    throw ValidationException('name', 'Name is required');
  }
  if (age < 0 || age > 150) {
    throw ValidationException('age', 'Invalid age');
  }
}

void main() {
  try {
    validateUser('', 200);
  } on ValidationException catch (e) {
    print('${e.field}: ${e.message}');
  } catch (e) {
    print('Unexpected error: $e');
  }
}
